124
00:12:06,450 --> 00:12:10,047
And then when ω will tend to infinity,

125
00:12:10,182 --> 00:12:12,982
this asymptote will be followed.

126
00:12:13,456 --> 00:12:16,742
We expect, in other words, 
something like that.

127
00:12:17,151 --> 00:12:20,502
These are right-handed waves.

128
00:12:21,471 --> 00:12:23,585
What about the left-handed waves?

129
00:12:23,585 --> 00:12:30,528
Well they do not exist for ω
that is in between Ωi and ωL

130
00:12:30,732 --> 00:12:33,028
and they have the same 
asymptotic behavior

131
00:12:33,028 --> 00:12:37,776
therefore at the low value of ω and K

132
00:12:37,776 --> 00:12:45,100
they will follow again, same asymptote 
then K will tend to infinity

133
00:12:45,623 --> 00:12:49,851
and then at the left-handed wave 
will appear again

134
00:12:49,938 --> 00:12:59,550
at ωL and will tend to infinity 
following this asymptote, ω/K = c

135
00:13:00,304 --> 00:13:02,761
These are the relationships between

136
00:13:02,761 --> 00:13:09,380
frequency and the wavenumber for 
both left-handed and right-handed waves.

137
00:13:10,802 --> 00:13:13,527
There is a range of frequencies 
where the right-handed waves

138
00:13:13,527 --> 00:13:17,508
display very interesting properties
and in this range of frequency

