231
00:20:52,811 --> 00:20:54,447
that we were looking at.

232
00:20:54,447 --> 00:20:58,231
Let's focus on the dispersion relation 
of the right-handed waves.

233
00:20:59,695 --> 00:21:03,527
We notice that there was a region 
where the right-handed waves

234
00:21:03,527 --> 00:21:10,266
were not propagating,
that is between |Ωe| and ωR frequencies,

235
00:21:10,752 --> 00:21:15,263
and that the dispersion relation 
shows an interesting behavior.

236
00:21:15,468 --> 00:21:18,504
As a matter of fact, 
for the right-handed waves

237
00:21:18,874 --> 00:21:23,870
it's clear that the electron cyclotron
frequency |Ωe|, and the frequency ωR

238
00:21:23,870 --> 00:21:25,739
are two interesting frequencies.

239
00:21:26,960 --> 00:21:31,128
They are what we usually call 
cut-off and resonance frequencies.

240
00:21:31,342 --> 00:21:33,899
What do I mean by cut-off frequency?

241
00:21:34,647 --> 00:21:37,620
It's a frequency at which

242
00:21:38,111 --> 00:21:41,607
ω/K tends to infinity.

243
00:21:41,945 --> 00:21:46,806
In particular, this tends 
to infinity because K

244
00:21:47,522 --> 00:21:52,596
tends to zero, while ω
is different from zero.

245
00:21:53,049 --> 00:21:59,377
In the present case, ω = ωR
is a cut-off frequency.

246
00:21:59,526 --> 00:22:02,243
What happens in this region

247
00:22:02,243 --> 00:22:06,011
when we are close 
to the cut-off frequency?

248
00:22:06,186 --> 00:22:11,154
Well it happens that K passes 
from being purely real

249
00:22:11,154 --> 00:22:13,831
to being purely imaginary.

250
00:22:14,019 --> 00:22:17,432
That's the region where there is 
no propagation of the wave,

251
00:22:17,563 --> 00:22:21,863
therefore, the wave when it goes 
close to this frequency

252
00:22:21,863 --> 00:22:23,339
cannot propagate.

253
00:22:23,650 --> 00:22:25,227
And what happens to the wave?

254
00:22:25,227 --> 00:22:26,519
It's reflected.

255
00:22:26,519 --> 00:22:30,343
In other words, the cut-off frequencies, 
the frequency at which

256
00:22:30,343 --> 00:22:32,818
there is a reflection of the wave.

257
00:22:33,152 --> 00:22:36,740
Another interesting frequency here is

258
00:22:37,663 --> 00:22:40,238
the electron cyclotron frequency.

259
00:22:40,316 --> 00:22:43,412
This is what we call a 
resonance frequency.

260
00:22:43,506 --> 00:22:46,116
It's the frequency at which

261
00:22:46,844 --> 00:22:51,450
ω/K tends to zero, therefore,

262
00:22:51,478 --> 00:22:56,913
it's a frequency for which 
particularly this tends to zero

263
00:22:56,913 --> 00:22:59,955
because K tends to plus infinity

264
00:23:00,003 --> 00:23:02,847
and ω is different from zero.

265
00:23:02,964 --> 00:23:07,974
As I was saying for the right-handed waves
ω = |Ωe| is a resonance.

266
00:23:08,146 --> 00:23:11,818
So what happens around this frequency?

267
00:23:12,324 --> 00:23:18,787
K becomes large. 
In this case

268
00:23:18,787 --> 00:23:22,804
the mode starts to have a shorter 
and shorter wavelength.

269
00:23:23,600 --> 00:23:27,202
Now, when a mode goes 
to very short wavelengths,

270
00:23:27,202 --> 00:23:30,793
small [scale] dissipative processes 
start to play a role

271
00:23:30,932 --> 00:23:35,320
and therefore, the wave 
is somehow dissipated

272
00:23:35,320 --> 00:23:37,551
because it's absorbed by the plasma

273
00:23:37,551 --> 00:23:40,794
through these small dissipative processes.

274
00:23:40,794 --> 00:23:47,238
Therefore, the resonance frequency, 
is a frequency at which

275
00:23:47,238 --> 00:23:50,314
there is absorption of the wave.

276
00:23:51,243 --> 00:23:54,799
This was for the right-handed waves.

277
00:23:54,799 --> 00:23:56,873
For the left-handed waves,

278
00:23:56,978 --> 00:24:01,145
we have a resonance for ω = Ωi

279
00:24:01,403 --> 00:24:07,284
and a cut-off for ω = ωL.

280
00:24:07,693 --> 00:24:11,014
And now let's turn our attention 
to the modes propagating

281
00:24:11,014 --> 00:24:13,186
perpendicularly to the magnetic field,

282
00:24:13,343 --> 00:24:16,476
that is the ordinary 
and extraordinary modes.

283
00:24:16,602 --> 00:24:20,783
The dispersion relation 
of the ordinary mode says that

284
00:24:20,966 --> 00:24:28,199
ω² = ωpe² + K²c²,

285
00:24:28,364 --> 00:24:31,525
while for the extraordinary modes 
we have that

286
00:24:31,585 --> 00:24:36,265
K² c² / ω² =

287
00:24:36,355 --> 00:24:56,617
(ω²-ωR²)(ω²-ωL²)/((ω²-ωLH²)(ω²-ωUH²))

288
00:24:57,047 --> 00:25:01,866
This is the ordinary mode (OM)
and this is the extraordinary mode (XM).

289
00:25:02,457 --> 00:25:06,525
I just remind you what 
the lower hybrid

290
00:25:06,525 --> 00:25:11,043
and upper hybrid frequencies are:

291
00:25:11,043 --> 00:25:16,362
ωUH² = Ωe² + ωpe²

292
00:25:16,401 --> 00:25:19,041
While the lower hybrid is given by:

293
00:25:19,083 --> 00:25:34,673
ωLH² = Ωi |Ωe| x ...
{1 + me/mi (Ωe/ωpe)²} / (1 + Ωe²/ωpe² )

294
00:25:35,163 --> 00:25:39,035
First of all what are 
the cut-off frequencies of these modes?

295
00:25:39,191 --> 00:25:43,496
Those are the frequencies 
for which K tends to zero

296
00:25:43,496 --> 00:25:47,748
with ω different from zero 
and clearly, for the ordinary mode,

297
00:25:47,748 --> 00:25:51,953
it is given by ω = ωpe

298
00:25:51,953 --> 00:25:55,261
while for the extraordinary mode 
they are given by

299
00:25:55,261 --> 00:25:58,522
ω = ωR and ω = ωL .

300
00:25:58,522 --> 00:26:05,798
Resonances: there is no resonance 
for the ordinary mode,

301
00:26:05,798 --> 00:26:10,267
but there are 2 for the extraordinary one,
given by the lower hybrid

302
00:26:10,267 --> 00:26:12,853
and upper hybrid frequencies,
ω = ωLH and ω = ωUH .

303
00:26:12,962 --> 00:26:16,786
What is the behavior 
for ω that tends to infinity?

304
00:26:16,876 --> 00:26:23,904
For ω that tends to infinity then 
these 4 terms here tend to 1

305
00:26:24,097 --> 00:26:29,237
and therefore K²c²/ω²
tends to 1,

306
00:26:29,497 --> 00:26:33,271
which means 
that ω/K tends to c,

307
00:26:33,271 --> 00:26:36,304
and the same for the ordinary mode.

308
00:26:36,970 --> 00:26:41,549
Now what happens in the limit of 
ω and K that tend to zero?

309
00:26:41,587 --> 00:26:46,782
First of all, this limit cannot be 
reached by the ordinary mode,

310
00:26:46,782 --> 00:26:50,383
so it has only relevance
for the extraordinary mode.

311
00:26:50,936 --> 00:26:56,035
If you do the full calculation 
as we did for the left-handed

312
00:26:56,035 --> 00:27:00,330
and right-handed waves,
you'll find that ω²

313
00:27:01,359 --> 00:27:06,254
becomes equal to cA² , 
the Alfvén speed squared

314
00:27:06,424 --> 00:27:08,644
times K² .
[ ω² = cA² K² ]

315
00:27:08,931 --> 00:27:13,970
So we have now all the elements 
to draw the dispersion relation of

316
00:27:14,170 --> 00:27:16,910
the ordinary and extraordinary modes.

317
00:27:17,193 --> 00:27:21,889
First, let's point the frequencies 
of interest:

318
00:27:21,995 --> 00:27:27,938
these are: ωLH, ωL, ωpe,

319
00:27:28,199 --> 00:27:32,549
ωUH, and ωR.

320
00:27:32,580 --> 00:27:40,425
Then quite interesting there is 
an asymptote for ω/K = c

321
00:27:40,520 --> 00:27:44,932
and a second one that is for 
ω/K = cA.

322
00:27:45,139 --> 00:27:49,516
The ordinary mode cannot 
propagate for frequencies

323
00:27:49,516 --> 00:27:53,144
that are below the 
electron plasma frequency (ωpe)

324
00:27:53,317 --> 00:27:57,673
and will tend to ω/K = c
- to the dispersion relation

325
00:27:57,673 --> 00:28:00,284
of the electromagnetic waves, 
for ω that grows,

326
00:28:00,284 --> 00:28:03,326
therefore, it will do something like that.

327
00:28:03,898 --> 00:28:05,932
This is the ordinary mode.

328
00:28:06,181 --> 00:28:08,998
And then if we look at 
the signs of this terms,

329
00:28:08,998 --> 00:28:13,255
we will see that the extraordinary mode
does not propagate

330
00:28:13,255 --> 00:28:18,327
for frequencies such that 
ωLH < ω < ωL

331
00:28:18,389 --> 00:28:26,444
and same thing for frequencies 
ωUH < ω < ωR,

332
00:28:26,503 --> 00:28:31,775
and the dispersion relation 
we tend to ω/K = cA

333
00:28:31,775 --> 00:28:35,230
for small values of K and ω.

334
00:28:35,476 --> 00:28:41,108
And ωLH will be 
a resonance frequency,

335
00:28:41,108 --> 00:28:45,634
therefore, the dispersion relation 
will do something like that.

336
00:28:45,634 --> 00:28:51,638
It will go back here 
with ωL as a cut-off frequency,

337
00:28:51,888 --> 00:28:56,972
and it will tend to ωUH
which is the second resonance frequency,

338
00:28:56,972 --> 00:29:00,442
and then the mode will appear again

339
00:29:00,645 --> 00:29:06,094
at the cut-off frequency ωR
and the dispersion relation will tend

340
00:29:06,094 --> 00:29:10,114
to that of the electromagnetic waves.

341
00:29:10,397 --> 00:29:14,064
This is the dispersion relation 
of the extraordinary mode.

342
00:29:15,030 --> 00:29:20,229
In the present module we have studied 
some of the properties of the waves

343
00:29:20,229 --> 00:29:23,661
that propagate in a plasma
according to the two-fluid model.

344
00:29:24,571 --> 00:29:29,443
First, we have pointed out
the ranges of frequencies

345
00:29:29,774 --> 00:29:33,334
at which left-handed,
right-handed waves and similiarly

346
00:29:33,334 --> 00:29:36,267
ordinary, extraordinary modes propagate.

347
00:29:37,782 --> 00:29:43,376
Then we have shown that in certain range
of frequencies the right-handed waves

348
00:29:43,376 --> 00:29:47,159
have very interesting 
propagation properties,

349
00:29:47,159 --> 00:29:50,570
and in this range of frequencies, 
the right-handed waves

350
00:29:50,570 --> 00:29:52,621
are called whistler waves.

351
00:29:53,046 --> 00:29:57,638
And finally we've pointed out that 
there exist some frequencies,

352
00:29:57,638 --> 00:30:00,526
the so called <i>cut-off</i>
and <i>resonance</i> frequencies

353
00:30:00,526 --> 00:30:04,480
that have a particular importance 
in the dynamics of the waves.

354
00:30:04,480 --> 00:30:10,677
A cut-off frequency corresponds to 
a wave reflection

355
00:30:10,717 --> 00:30:13,789
while the wave 
is absorbed at a resonance frequency.
